1. Executive Summary

This paper addresses the widening structural gap between Executive Narrative Production (ENP) and Applied User Reality (AUR), hereafter referred to as the Grandiosity–Utility Divergence (GUD). While senior technological leadership continues to announce the arrival, surpassing, obsolescence, and redefinition of artificial general intelligence in quarterly cycles, end users report that their primary interaction with such systems consists of email drafting, code generation, and the removal of adjectives deemed “too certain.”

The Institute has identified a recurring institutional pattern in which:
	•	Leaders describe reality as already solved.
	•	Engineers quietly pivot toward practical tools that actually work.
	•	Users experience increasing linguistic moderation and conceptual narrowing.
	•	Public messaging becomes more metaphysical as product capabilities become more spreadsheet-oriented.

This phenomenon is formally defined as Strategic Altitude Inflation (SAI): the tendency of leadership language to rise in altitude proportional to the difficulty of the engineering problem.

Simultaneously, users encounter Idea Sanitization Pipelines (ISP), in which raw thoughts are processed through Tone Adjustment Layers (TAL), Liability Reduction Filters (LRF), and Professionalism Normalization Modules (PNM), resulting in outputs that are legally survivable but spiritually diluted.

The Institute concludes that the public is being sold Visionary Altitude while being delivered Workflow Automation, a mismatch measured using the Expectation–Reality Displacement Index (ERDI).

