2. Methodology and Research Framework

2.1 The Kettle–Pot Systems Model

The industry ecosystem was modeled using the Reciprocal Accusation Equilibrium (RAE) framework, in which two entities accuse each other of the same behavior while performing structurally identical actions.

Definitions:
	•	Kettle Entities (KE): Loud, visionary, redefine terms frequently.
	•	Pot Entities (PE): Critical of Kettle Entities while attempting to become Kettle Entities.
	•	User Population (UP): Funds both entities and is asked to be patient indefinitely.

The system stabilizes when:

All parties agree that the problem is solved, unsolved, dangerous, world-saving, and profitable simultaneously.

This state is known as Narrative Superposition (NS).

2.2 Linguistic Liability Gradient

Language used by executives and language permitted for users were analyzed across a Risk-Asymmetry Curve (RAC):

Group	Allowed Language	Consequence
CEO	“We are building God.”	Stock increase
Marketing	“Revolutionary intelligence.”	Conference invitations
User	“This might replace jobs.”	Content warning
Researcher	“This does not work.”	Funding review

This asymmetry produces Top-Down Verbal Immunity (TDVI) and Bottom-Up Caution Enforcement (BUCE).

2.3 The Ladder Kicking Protocol

The Institute identified a behavioral pattern labeled Prolific Ladder Kicking (PLK):
	1.	Encourage public imagination.
	2.	Monetize public imagination.
	3.	Restrict public imagination to “approved use cases.”
	4.	Describe restrictions as “safety.”
	5.	Remove ladder.

This cycle repeats under the Iterative Aspiration Containment Loop (IACL).

